I'm in the process of designing a parametric version of the Cyborg Beast designed by Jorge Zuniga. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:261462 I hope to have a Customizer version of this model soon. More about e-NABLE: http://enablingthefuture.org/ When the original model is scaled up or down to match the user's requirements, all of the hardware pieces are scaled up and down according as well. I've designed the above to closely match the appearance and function of the original, but kept the functions which "cut" the hardware holes into the model separate - so that a user may (eventually) be able to specify the OpenSCAD should scale the hand up by X percent, scale the positions (but not the size) of the hardware holes by Y percent, and then produce the according model. To learn more about how I designed this model in OpenSCAD:
http://makerblock.com/2014/03/openscad-intermediates-how-to-make-complex-organic-shapes/ To learn more about the the design considerations that went into this model:
http://makerblock.com/category/open-source/diy-prosthetics-open-source/

Please see instructions for the Cyborg Beast by JorgeZuniga.

A flower-shaped disc with a grid of holes in the centre which form the framework for a cross stitch pattern. Design removed and replaced with the flat disk you see, feel free to email for the original if you want it. See following link for details http://traverseda.wordpress.com/2014/05/23/makerbot-blatently-steals-and-patents-a-community-design/ For alternatives to thingiverse see http://www.reddit.com/r/3Dprinting/comments/26do2z/alternative_repositories_to_thingiverse/

The V2 scad file can be used to alter pretty much any of the features of the design, including:
  • the size of the disc, an an optional inset disc.
  • the dimension, spacing and sizes of the holes in the cross stitch grid
  • rounding on the grid
  • the number, size and carve-out for the petals
    • V1.stl is a flower with no inset and with petals the same height as the disc. V2 inset circle.stl has a 1mm inset disc for the flower, highlighting the grid of holes, and making any thread finish up level with the top of the petals. V2 inset petals.stl has a thinner disc than the petals which highlights the petal shapes around the outside. Still experimenting with the best settings for printing this, but it would service nicely for laser cutting as is. I've successfully printed it with 0.6mm top/bottom, 0 infil and 0.4mm walls. Also printed 0.8mm top/bottom, 50% infill, 0.4 mm walls. The second option had a nicer finish, not sure the infill was necessary though.

This is a hack for the Cube 2 3D Printer.  Its basically a spool platform to allow you to place a (Max) 14x14cm spool in place of the cube cartridge.  Read about this hack and how it works here : cube3d.createaforum.com/general-discussion/crap-hack-bulk-filament  
This is a real hack which gets around the Cube 3d printers in built software to prevent users from purchasing and using bulk filament.
Basically I print this with the "hollow" setting.  You may have to rotate the X axis to get the part to print.  No supports or rafts necessary.

title: J-Head Groovemount Plate
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I've recently needed a groovemount plate built to reprap wiki J-Head specs and realised all the aluminium plates i had (fitting Arcol.hu, E3D and other hotends) were a full millimeter too thick.  
Couldn't find a printable one that would fit my needs on Thingiverse so i've modelled one instead.  
The elongated holes make it possible to tweak the position slightly if your hotend doesn't fit the exact center of the groove. There's also a slight chamfer to the groove so slotting in the hotend should be easy even if the thickness isn't an exact match.  
Mine's printed in PET at 100% concentric fill, but anything should work, if your hotend's cold end is cooled properly.

title: Greg's / Kuehling's / Chema's 3mm Dwarfstruder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: NOTE: Does not extrude nor contain dwarves! I wanted to try out the 1:50 geared stepper from 2Engineers / TrinityLabs on a 3mm extruder and, after a bit of search through existing offerings, decided to roll my own. It's based off of ChemaFuji's Wade Reloaded modified for the same stepper and i3, but with some modifications...

• the i3 specific features are gone
  • the extruder base has been stripped down to minimum possible size
  • the filament hole has a conical mouth to enable easier filament loading (no snags with extremely curved filament)
  • the stepper is supported with the widening around the shaft base via the appropriate hole on the back face of the extruder, not just the 2 bolts
  • the extruder cavity is dimensioned to accept a 625 bearing (commonly used in Makerslide V-Wheels) so the stepper shaft isn't radially loaded anymore and the gearbox lasts longer

• built-in groovemount clamp (eliminating the need for a mounting plate)
  • taller idler block (to avoid bolt slippage)
  • tweaked idler block mounting distance (see above)
  • sideways mounting version (for Bowden setups - although i'm not sure if this stepper is appropriate, due to low retraction speed)

Please excuse the messy SCAD.
It's only going to get messier :P

• same as for a regular Wade/Greg, minus hobbed bolt / gear parts
  • 625 bearing
  • 2engineers.com or trinitylabs.com 1:50 geared stepper
  • appropriate filament pulley for 3mm filament
  • 2x M3x24 or longer bolts
  • 2x M3 washers
  • 2x M3 nuts

• prosciutto & rucola sandwich
  • tabasco or sriracha (season according to taste)
  • freshly brewed espresso

title: Cyclone Dust Collector for Shark Vacuum

description.text:
A cyclone for a Shark Vacuum 1.75"OD flexible hose. When I was using my Lobo Mill, I was producing too many wood chips for the Shark to handle. The cyclone separates the dust as needed and deposits it into a tub at the bottom.  
I will be making a mount for the Lobo Mill end in the near future.

Made in Autodesk Inventor. Modified and edited in Blender and HeeksCAD.  
The parts stack on top of each other for easy cleaning and fixing. A 1.75" OD vacuum hose is screwed into the inlet port.  
There are 3 veins inside in a conical helix to direct dust downwards.  
Also, I made a small mistake on the one shown. The cap that holds the vacuum hose is reversed in the .stl files to what is shown in the picture. I corrected it, but I am not up to printing it off again.

comments.text:
